Good, I have the ADR style. Now writing ADR-076:  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/Tengu/tengu-cockpit/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-opus/docs/adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md', content='# ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow — Driver / Navigator Pair Programming\n\n**Status:** Proposed — 2026-04-24\n**Date:** 2026-04-24\n**Related:** ADR-012 (multi-agent), ADR-063 (coordinator mode), PlanMode (`duh/kernel/plan_mode.py`)\n\n## Context\n\nUsers routinely ask D.U.H. to "write a test first, then the code." Today the\nsingle-agent loop can technically do that, but nothing enforces the\ndiscipline: the same model writes the test and the code in one continuous\nassistant turn, so the "RED" step frequently collapses into "wrote\nalready-passing test + implementation in the same message." The failing\ntest — the whole reason TDD works — never actually fails.\n\nWe already have two abstractions that get us 80% of the way there:\n\n- **`PlanMode`** (`duh/kernel/plan_mode.py`) — a state-machine wrapper\n  around an `Engine` that strictly sequences phases, forces\n  `tool_choice="none"` when the phase is deliberative, and yields the\n  same event shape as `Engine.run()`.\n- **Agents** (`duh/agents.py`, ADR-012) — each "agent" is just another\n  `Engine` with a system-prompt overlay and its own conversation.\n\nWhat is missing is an orchestrator that sequences **two** agents against\nthe same working tree, with **test execution as a hard gate** between\nphases. A single-model implementation cannot reliably gate on a real\nprocess exit code, because the model that wrote the test is also the one\ndeciding whether the test "counts as failing."\n\n## Decision\n\nAdd a **Double-Agent TDD Mode** — a new kernel-level orchestrator,\nmodelled on `PlanMode`, that drives two cooperating `Engine` instances\nthrough the six phases of red-green-refactor:\n\n| # | Phase | Actor      | Tool access | Hard gate on exit |\n|---|-------|------------|-------------|-------------------|\n| 1 | `SPEC`           | Navigator | `tool_choice="none"` | spec is non-empty |\n| 2 | `RED`            | Driver    | full tools           | **test command exits non-zero** |\n| 3 | `GREEN`          | Driver    | full tools           | **test command exits zero** |\n| 4 | `REFACTOR_PLAN`  | Navigator | `tool_choice="none"` | plan is non-empty |\n| 5 | `REFACTOR_APPLY` | Driver    | full tools           | at least one file changed since GREEN |\n| 6 | `VALIDATE`       | Navigator | full tools           | **test command exits zero** AND refactor plan items mentioned in the navigator\'s summary |\n\nThe flow is **strict**: a phase cannot start until the previous phase\'s\ngate has passed. If the RED phase\'s test unexpectedly passes, the\nNavigator is re-invoked to tighten the spec — this is the\n"spec-was-not-tight-enough" loop from the task brief.\n\n### Contract between Driver and Navigator\n\nThe two agents never talk to the model directly — they talk through\n`TddMode`. The contract is:\n\n- **Shared state** (owned by `TddMode`, not either engine):\n  - `description: str` — the user\'s feature request\n  - `spec: str` — the Navigator\'s test spec (set in phase 1)\n  - `test_command: list[str]` — argv for the test runner; defaults to\n    `["pytest", "-x", "--no-header"]`\n  - `refactor_plan: str` — the Navigator\'s refactor suggestion (set in\n    phase 4)\n  - `history: list[PhaseResult]` — one entry per phase transition,\n    including the agent that ran, the resulting text, and (for test\n    phases) the captured stdout/stderr/exit code\n\n- **Per-phase prompt templates** (module-level constants on\n  `duh/kernel/tdd_mode.py`, mirroring `PLAN_PROMPT_PREFIX`):\n  - `SPEC_PROMPT` — Navigator drafts a tight, minimal test spec\n  - `RED_PROMPT` — Driver writes a failing test implementing `spec`\n  - `GREEN_PROMPT` — Driver writes the **minimum** code to pass the\n    test; refactoring is explicitly forbidden at this phase\n  - `REFACTOR_PROPOSE_PROMPT` — Navigator proposes a refactor, referring\n    to concrete files/lines\n  - `REFACTOR_APPLY_PROMPT` — Driver applies the Navigator\'s refactor\n    verbatim; no scope creep\n  - `VALIDATE_PROMPT` — Navigator confirms the refactor landed and tests\n    still pass\n\n- **Agent overlays**: Driver and Navigator are built from the existing\n  `AGENT_OVERLAYS` dict — Driver uses `coder`, Navigator uses `reviewer`.\n  Both inherit the parent\'s model by default (ADR-012 tier rules).\n\n- **Events**: `TddMode` yields the same event dicts as `Engine.run()`,\n  plus two new event types:\n  - `{"type": "tdd_phase", "phase": "RED", "actor": "driver"}` — emitted\n    on every phase entry\n  - `{"type": "tdd_gate", "phase": "RED", "passed": bool,\n      "exit_code": int, "stdout": str, "stderr": str}` — emitted after\n    each gate check\n\n- **Observability**: the RED-phase gate surfaces the assertion failure\n  distinctly from GREEN by tagging the event with the phase name; the\n  REPL/TUI renderer colorises RED-gate passes green (because a failing\n  test at RED is *success*) and GREEN-gate passes green (because a\n  passing test at GREEN is *success*). Failures at either phase are\n  surfaced with the raw pytest output attached.\n\n### User-facing triggers\n\nThree entry points — mirroring how `PlanMode` is wired today:\n\n1. **Slash command `/tdd`** in the REPL/TUI:\n   ```\n   /tdd <feature description>       # propose a spec, stop for approval\n   /tdd approve                     # Navigator spec is accepted; run RED → GREEN\n   /tdd refactor                    # run REFACTOR_PLAN → REFACTOR_APPLY → VALIDATE\n   /tdd show                        # print the current phase + spec + history\n   /tdd clear                       # reset state\n   /tdd --test "pytest tests/foo"   # override the test command\n   ```\n2. **CLI subcommand `duh tdd`** — one-shot run, intended for CI:\n   ```\n   duh tdd "cache LRU eviction should drop oldest"\n   duh tdd --test "pytest tests/unit/test_cache.py" "LRU eviction"\n   duh tdd --auto "feature"     # no interactive approval, run all 6 phases\n   ```\n3. **Public Python API** — `TddMode(driver_engine, navigator_engine)`\n   mirrors `PlanMode(engine)` for SDK users and tests.\n\n### Why two Engines, not two prompts on one Engine\n\nThree reasons:\n\n1. **Context separation** — the Navigator\'s reviewer-mode system prompt\n   actively discourages writing code, while the Driver\'s coder-mode\n   prompt discourages hedging. Mixing them in one conversation dilutes\n   both.\n2. **Honest hand-off** — when the Navigator sees the Driver\'s test, it\n   is re-reading the file via Read/Grep tools, not recalling what it\n   "wrote." This is what makes the pair review valuable.\n3. **Cost tuning** — the Navigator can run on `small` (cheap review) and\n   the Driver on `medium` (careful implementation), configurable via\n   `--navigator-model` / `--driver-model` without touching the harness.\n\n## Alternatives considered\n\n### A. Single Engine with a system-prompt switch per phase\n\nReject. Tried informally — the model conflates phases because the\nconversation history contains the previous phase\'s work. The refactor\nphase in particular degenerates into "keep the code the same" because\nthe model has already committed to it.\n\n### B. Reuse `PlanMode` with a 6-step plan\n\nReject. `PlanMode` models a single agent executing its own plan. The\ncritical property of TDD — that the *reviewer* is a distinct voice —\ncannot be expressed as a plan. The plan-execution step has no concept\nof "wait, re-run the tests and block if they pass."\n\n### C. Drive via `SwarmTool`\n\nReject. `SwarmTool` is for **parallel** agent fan-out. TDD is strictly\nsequential, and each phase gates the next. Using `asyncio.gather` here\nwould hide the sequencing bug this feature exists to solve.\n\n### D. Let the model call a hypothetical `run_tdd_phase` tool\n\nReject. The single biggest failure mode in the status-quo "just ask for\nTDD" flow is the model skipping the RED-must-fail gate. Delegating the\ngate to a tool the model chooses when to call re-creates that failure\nmode. The gate **must** live outside the model\'s decision loop.\n\n## Consequences\n\n### Positive\n\n- Real TDD discipline: the RED phase is now gated on a real non-zero\n  exit code. If the Driver writes a test that already passes, the\n  harness refuses to advance and asks the Navigator to tighten the spec.\n- Reuses every existing abstraction: `Engine`, `Deps`, `PlanMode`-style\n  state machine, `AGENT_OVERLAYS`, `get_all_tools`. No new providers,\n  no new tool-execution layer.\n- Works with every provider D.U.H. supports, including the deterministic\n  `stub` provider — so the end-to-end test in the unit suite runs\n  offline.\n- Transparent CLI: `duh tdd <feature>` is a single command for CI use;\n  the REPL `/tdd` flow is for interactive pair-programming.\n\n### Negative\n\n- Two model calls per phase => higher cost than single-agent mode for\n  small tasks. Mitigated by the per-agent tier knobs.\n- Relies on `subprocess.run(test_command)` for the gate. If a user\'s\n  test harness is not command-line runnable, this flow does not apply.\n\n## Acceptance criteria\n\n1. `duh/kernel/tdd_mode.py` exposes a `TddMode` class with states\n   `EMPTY, SPEC, RED, GREEN, REFACTOR_PLAN, REFACTOR_APPLY, VALIDATE,\n   DONE` as an `Enum`, mirroring `PlanState`.\n2. The state machine refuses out-of-order transitions (e.g. cannot enter\n   GREEN until the RED gate has fired and failed, i.e. the test\n   actually failed).\n3. The RED phase emits a `tdd_gate` event with `passed=True` when the\n   test\'s exit code is **non-zero** (the "failing test is the success\n   signal" inversion), and re-invokes the Navigator\'s SPEC phase if the\n   test passes.\n4. The Navigator\'s refactor suggestion is captured as `refactor_plan`\n   and prepended to the Driver\'s REFACTOR_APPLY prompt; the apply-phase\n   prompt template includes the literal text of `refactor_plan`.\n5. A CLI flag `--test <cmd>` is honoured on the `duh tdd` subcommand and\n   defaults to `pytest -x --no-header`.\n6. Tests cover phase-transition ordering, RED-vs-GREEN event tagging,\n   the refactor-actually-applied contract, and a full end-to-end run\n   against the `stub` provider.\n')
  [33m> TodoWrite[0m(todos=[{'id': 'adr', 'text': 'Write ADR-076 for Double-Agent TDD flow', 'status': 'done'}, {'id': 'impl', 'text': 'Implement duh/kernel/tdd_mode.py (TddMode with six-phase state machine)', 'status': 'in_progress'}, {'id': 'cli', 'text': 'Wire /tdd slash command + duh tdd subcommand', 'status': 'pending'}, {'id': 'tests', 'text': 'Write unit tests covering six-phase contract', 'status': 'pending'}, {'id': 'docs', 'text': 'Update README + docs/wiki/ + slash-command help', 'status': 'pending'}, {'id': 'verify', 'text': 'Run tests to verify', 'status': 'pending'}])
