Now add wiki page and sidebar entry:  [33m> Write[0m(file_path='/Users/nomind/Code/Tengu/tengu-cockpit/benchmarks/double-agent-tdd/worktrees/duh-opus/docs/wiki/Double-Agent-TDD.md', content='# Double-Agent TDD\n\n## Overview\n\nD.U.H. supports a strict **red-green-refactor** flow driven by *two* cooperating agents — a **Driver** and a **Navigator** — pair-programming through the classic TDD cycle. The authoritative design document is [ADR-076](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md).\n\nThe feature exists because the single-agent "just ask for TDD" pattern reliably fails: the same model writes the test *and* the implementation in one assistant turn, so the RED step — the whole reason TDD works — never actually fails. The double-agent flow fixes this by gating every phase on a **real subprocess test-run**. The model cannot decide what "failing" means; the harness does.\n\n## Roles\n\n| Role          | Agent overlay | Tool access per phase             | Responsibility                               |\n|---------------|--------------|-----------------------------------|-----------------------------------------------|\n| **Driver**    | `coder`       | Full tools (Read / Edit / Write / Bash)  | Writes the failing test, writes the minimum code to pass it, applies the Navigator\'s refactor. |\n| **Navigator** | `reviewer`    | `tool_choice="none"` during SPEC and REFACTOR_PLAN; full tools during VALIDATE | Drafts the test spec, proposes refactors, validates the final state. |\n\nBoth agents are just `Engine` instances with different system prompts (ADR-012). There is no new provider, no new tool layer, no new runtime — everything reuses the existing kernel abstractions. That means every capability you already have (MCP servers, hooks, permissions, plan mode, etc.) works inside `/tdd` and `duh tdd` without modification.\n\n## The six phases\n\nThe flow is a strict state machine. Every transition is guarded; out-of-order calls raise `ValueError`.\n\n```\nEMPTY  ─▶ SPEC  ─▶ RED  ─▶ GREEN  ─▶ REFACTOR_PLAN  ─▶ REFACTOR_APPLY  ─▶ DONE\n   ▲                │\n   └─ RED unexpectedly passes (spec too loose → Navigator re-drafts)\n```\n\n| # | Phase            | Actor     | Gate                                               |\n|---|------------------|-----------|----------------------------------------------------|\n| 1 | `SPEC`           | Navigator | Spec text non-empty.                               |\n| 2 | `RED`            | Driver    | Test command exits **non-zero** (failing test is success). |\n| 3 | `GREEN`          | Driver    | Test command exits **zero**.                       |\n| 4 | `REFACTOR_PLAN`  | Navigator | Plan text non-empty.                               |\n| 5 | `REFACTOR_APPLY` | Driver    | Refactor plan was present (can\'t apply nothing).   |\n| 6 | `VALIDATE`       | Navigator | Test command exits **zero**.                       |\n\nThe RED/GREEN asymmetry is the heart of TDD: a test that passes at RED means the spec doesn\'t actually discriminate the feature. The harness short-circuits back to `EMPTY` and the Navigator is invited to tighten the spec. The `spec_revisions` counter is observable via `/tdd status` or `TddMode.spec_revisions` for telemetry.\n\n## CLI — `duh tdd`\n\nOne-shot, non-interactive, intended for CI or "I have 10 minutes, ship it" sessions:\n\n```bash\nduh tdd "<feature description>"\n```\n\n### Flags\n\n| Flag | Default | Purpose |\n|---|---|---|\n| `--test "<cmd>"` | `pytest -x --no-header` | Test command run at each gate. Shell-split with `shlex`. |\n| `--driver-model <name>` | same as `--model` | Override the Driver\'s model (tier alias OK). |\n| `--navigator-model <name>` | same as `--model` | Override the Navigator\'s model. |\n| `--model`, `--provider`, `--max-turns`, `--debug`, … | inherited from global `duh` flags | standard plumbing |\n\n### Example\n\n```bash\nduh tdd --test "pytest tests/unit/test_cache.py -x" \\\n        --driver-model medium --navigator-model small \\\n        "LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full"\n```\n\nSample output (abbreviated):\n\n```\nduh tdd — provider=anthropic driver=claude-sonnet-4-6 navigator=claude-haiku-4-5\n  test command: pytest tests/unit/test_cache.py -x\n  feature     : LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full\n\n== SPEC (navigator) ==\n== RED (driver) ==\n  [RED gate ✓] exit=1 gate_passed=True\n== GREEN (driver) ==\n  [GREEN gate ✓] exit=0 gate_passed=True\n== REFACTOR_PLAN (navigator) ==\n== REFACTOR_APPLY (driver) ==\n== VALIDATE (navigator) ==\n  [VALIDATE gate ✓] exit=0 gate_passed=True\n\nTDD state: DONE\n  feature: LRU cache drops the oldest entry when full\n  ...\n```\n\n### Exit codes\n\n| Exit | Meaning |\n|---|---|\n| 0 | `TddState.DONE` — all six phases passed. |\n| 1 | Flow did not reach DONE (gate failure, or spec was revised and the run ended before re-approval). |\n| 4 | `PROVIDER_ERROR` — no API key / auth available. |\n\n## REPL — `/tdd`\n\nInside `duh` (interactive REPL or TUI):\n\n```text\n/tdd <feature>            # run the full six-phase flow inline\n/tdd status               # show the flow wiring + default test command\n/tdd help                 # full syntax\n```\n\n`/tdd <feature>` is implemented as a REPL lifecycle signal (same mechanism `/plan` uses). The REPL builds a Driver + Navigator as lightweight sibling Engines of the active session and streams phase / gate events inline. Tool calls made by the Driver (Edit, Write, Bash, …) go through the same approval + audit plumbing as normal REPL turns.\n\n## Python API\n\n```python\nfrom duh.kernel.deps import Deps\nfrom duh.kernel.engine import Engine, EngineConfig\nfrom duh.kernel.tdd_mode import TddMode\n\ndriver = Engine(\n    deps=Deps(call_model=my_provider.stream, run_tool=executor.run, approve=approver.check),\n    config=EngineConfig(model="claude-sonnet-4-6", system_prompt=coder_prompt, tools=tools),\n)\nnavigator = Engine(\n    deps=Deps(call_model=my_provider.stream, run_tool=executor.run, approve=approver.check),\n    config=EngineConfig(model="claude-haiku-4-5", system_prompt=reviewer_prompt, tools=tools),\n)\n\ntdd = TddMode(\n    driver=driver,\n    navigator=navigator,\n    test_command=["pytest", "-x", "tests/unit/test_cache.py"],\n)\n\nasync for event in tdd.run_all("LRU cache drops oldest entry"):\n    print(event)\n\nassert tdd.state.name == "DONE"\n```\n\n`TddMode` exposes one coroutine per phase (`draft_spec`, `red`, `green`, `propose_refactor`, `refactor_apply`, `validate`) and two convenience drivers (`refactor`, `run_all`). Every coroutine is an async generator yielding the same event dicts the `Engine` yields, plus two new types:\n\n| Event type    | Keys                                                          | Fires                  |\n|---------------|---------------------------------------------------------------|------------------------|\n| `tdd_phase`   | `phase`, `actor`                                              | Entry to each phase.   |\n| `tdd_gate`    | `phase`, `passed`, `test_passed`, `exit_code`, `stdout`, `stderr` | After the gate runs.   |\n\nFor tests, you can swap in a `test_runner` callable (signature `(cmd, cwd) -> GateResult`) so unit tests don\'t shell out. See `tests/unit/test_tdd_mode.py` for the pattern.\n\n## Design decisions\n\nSee [ADR-076](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md) for the full context, alternatives considered, and acceptance criteria. In brief:\n\n- **Two Engines, not one** — a single Engine with a system-prompt switch per phase conflates roles; the Navigator has to re-read what the Driver wrote from disk, not recall it from shared context, and that\'s where the review value comes from.\n- **Gate is external to the model** — the single biggest failure mode of the "just ask for TDD" flow is the model skipping the RED-must-fail check. Putting the check in a subprocess call the harness controls (not a tool the model can choose to skip) is the only reliable fix.\n- **Reuse existing abstractions** — Driver = `Engine` with `coder` overlay; Navigator = `Engine` with `reviewer` overlay; state machine = same shape as `PlanMode`. Zero new infrastructure.\n\n## See also\n\n- [ADR-076: Double-Agent TDD Flow](../adrs/ADR-076-double-agent-tdd-flow.md) — the contract between Driver and Navigator.\n- [Multi-Agent Guide](Multi-Agent.md) — how agent overlays work in general.\n- [ADR-012: Multi-Agent](../adrs/ADR-012-multi-agent.md) — why agents are just Engines.\n- `duh/kernel/tdd_mode.py` — the implementation.\n- `tests/unit/test_tdd_mode.py` — the six-phase contract test suite.\n')
